               <p class="text-[#2E2E2E] text-center"> Heart disease encompasses a range of conditions that impact the heart's function. From coronary artery disease to heart failure, each condition requires unique attention. Coronary artery disease, characterized by the buildup of plaque in the arteries, is a common form of heart disease. Heart attacks, heart failure, and arrhythmias are among the critical complications associated with this condition.

Key Factors Contributing to Heart Disease:
Unhealthy Diet:
Diets high in saturated fats, trans fats, sodium, and low in fruits, vegetables, and whole grains contribute to heart disease. Adopting a heart-healthy diet is crucial.

Lack of Physical Activity:
Sedentary lifestyles increase the risk of heart disease. Regular exercise strengthens the heart, improves circulation, and helps maintain a healthy weight.

Smoking and Tobacco Use:
Tobacco use is a major risk factor for heart disease. Smoking damages blood vessels, raises blood pressure, and reduces the effectiveness of the heart.

Excessive Alcohol Consumption:
While moderate alcohol consumption may have cardiovascular benefits, excessive drinking can contribute to heart disease. Limit alcohol intake to promote heart health.

High Blood Pressure:
Hypertension strains the heart and arteries, leading to an increased risk of heart disease. Regular monitoring and management of blood pressure are crucial.

Diabetes:
Uncontrolled diabetes can damage blood vessels and the heart. Managing blood sugar levels is essential for preventing heart disease in individuals with diabetes.</p>
